Date: 0/0/1890
Source: Gold-Dredging in Otago
Author: BEAL
Vol / Page: 47
Edition:
Quote: The spoon-dredge consisted of a large hide affixed to an iron rim with a sharp shovel-faced cutting-edge, and holding about a barrowful: this was affixed to the end of a long, strong, but light pole, about twenty feet in length. This was worked from a barge by means of a hand winch and tackle. ... [48] The old system of spoon-dredging died out (such a thing as a spoon-dredge being hard to find at the present time). -->1906 NZ Mining Handbook 34 Spoon dredges were used in this and other countries for many years, but the employment of bucket dredges to work the auriferous gravels in the beds of rivers was first introduced in New Zealand.
